WEBVTT

00:22.320 --> 00:27.140
IX. Mrs. Rachel Lind is Properly Horrified

00:28.720 --> 00:34.380
Anne had been a fortnight at Green Gables before Mrs. Lind arrived to inspect her. Mrs.

00:34.600 --> 00:39.820
Rachel, to do her justice, was not to blame for this. A severe and unseasonable attack

00:39.820 --> 00:44.600
of grip had confined that good lady to her house ever since the occasion of her last

00:44.600 --> 00:50.260
visit to Green Gables. Mrs. Rachel was not often sick and had a well-defined contempt

00:50.260 --> 00:55.800
for people who were, but grip, she asserted, was like no other illness on earth and could

00:55.800 --> 01:01.680
only be interpreted as one of the special visitations of Providence. As soon as her

01:01.680 --> 01:06.520
doctor allowed her to put her foot out of doors, she hurried up to Green Gables, bursting

01:06.520 --> 01:11.540
with curiosity to see Matthew and Marilla's orphan, concerning whom all sorts of stories

01:11.540 --> 01:17.700
and suppositions had gone abroad in Avonlea. Anne had made good use of every waking moment

01:17.700 --> 01:22.780
of that fortnight. Already she was acquainted with every tree and shrub about the place.

01:23.480 --> 01:27.960
She had discovered that a lane opened out below the apple orchard and ran up through

01:27.960 --> 01:33.260
a belt of woodland, and she had explored it to its furthest end in all its delicious vagaries

01:33.260 --> 01:39.520
of brook and bridge, fir coppice and wild cherry arch, corners thick with fern, and

01:39.520 --> 01:45.160
branching byways of maple and mountain ash. She had made friends with the spring down

01:45.160 --> 01:51.040
in the hollow, that wonderful deep, clear, icy-cold spring. It was set about with smooth

01:51.040 --> 01:57.320
red sandstones and rimmed in by great palm-like clumps of water fern, and beyond it was a

01:57.320 --> 02:04.000
log bridge over the brook. That bridge led Anne's dancing feet up over a wooded hill

02:04.000 --> 02:09.840
beyond where perpetual twilight rained under the straight, thick-growing firs and spruces.

02:10.460 --> 02:16.560
The only flowers there were myriads of delicate june bells, those shyest and sweetest of woodland

02:16.560 --> 02:22.660
blooms, and a few pale aerial star-flowers like the spirits of last year's blossoms.

02:23.940 --> 02:28.940
Gossamers glimmered like threads of silver among the trees, and the fir boughs and tassels

02:28.940 --> 02:36.820
seemed to utter friendly speech. All these raptured voyages of exploration were made

02:36.820 --> 02:42.560
in the odd half-hours which she was allowed for play, and Anne talked Matthew and Marilla

02:42.560 --> 02:49.060
half-deaf over her discoveries. Not that Matthew complained, to be sure. He listened to it

02:49.060 --> 02:54.620
all with a wordless smile of enjoyment on his face. Marilla permitted the chatter until

02:54.620 --> 02:59.080
she found herself becoming too interested in it, whereupon she always promptly quenched

02:59.080 --> 03:05.860
Anne by a curt command to hold her tongue. Anne was out in the orchard when Mrs. Rachel

03:05.860 --> 03:11.340
came, wandering at her own sweet will through the lush tremulous grasses splashed with ruddy

03:11.340 --> 03:16.560
evening sunshine, so that good lady had an excellent chance to talk her illness fully

03:16.560 --> 03:21.960
over, describing every ache and pulse beat with such evident enjoyment that Marilla thought

03:21.960 --> 03:28.200
even grip must bring its compensations. When details were exhausted, Mrs. Rachel introduced

03:28.200 --> 03:29.800
the real reason of her call.

03:30.860 --> 03:33.700
I've been hearing some surprising things about you and Matthew.

03:35.600 --> 03:40.100
I don't suppose you are any more surprised than I am myself, said Marilla. I'm getting

03:40.100 --> 03:41.540
over my surprise now.

03:43.280 --> 03:47.700
It was too bad there was such a mistake, said Mrs. Rachel sympathetically. Couldn't you

03:47.700 --> 03:48.540
have sent her back?

03:50.060 --> 03:55.380
I suppose we could, but we decided not to. Matthew took a fancy to her, and I must say

03:55.380 --> 04:00.060
I like her myself, though I admit she has her faults. The house seems a different place

04:00.060 --> 04:02.320
already. She's a real bright little thing.

04:04.480 --> 04:09.080
Marilla said more than she had intended to say when she began, for she read disapproval

04:09.080 --> 04:10.480
in Mrs. Rachel's expression.

04:12.320 --> 04:17.020
It's a great responsibility you've taken on yourself, said that lady gloomily, especially

04:17.020 --> 04:21.340
when you've never had any experience with children. You don't know much about her or

04:21.340 --> 04:25.260
her real disposition, I suppose, and there's no guessing how a child like that will turn

04:25.260 --> 04:28.220
out. But I don't want to discourage you, I'm sure, Marilla.

04:29.700 --> 04:35.020
I'm not feeling discouraged, was Marilla's dry response. When I make up my mind to do

04:35.020 --> 04:39.840
something, it stays made up. I suppose you'd like to see Anne. I'll call her in.

04:41.400 --> 04:47.420
Anne came running in presently, her face sparkling with the delight of her orchard rovings, but

04:47.420 --> 04:52.800
abashed at finding herself in the unexpected presence of her stranger, she halted confusedly

04:52.800 --> 04:58.220
inside the door. She certainly was an odd-looking little creature in the short, tight, wincey

04:58.220 --> 05:03.740
dress she had worn from the asylum, below which her thin legs seemed ungracefully long.

05:04.480 --> 05:09.560
Her freckles were more numerous and obtrusive than ever. The wind had ruffled her hatless

05:09.560 --> 05:14.040
hair into over-brilliant disorder. It had never looked redder than at that moment.

05:16.260 --> 05:20.140
Well, they didn't pick you for your looks, that's sure and certain, was Mrs. Rachel Lynn's

05:20.140 --> 05:26.040
emphatic comment. Mrs. Rachel was one of those delightful and popular people who pride themselves

05:26.040 --> 05:28.380
on speaking their mind without fear or favor.

05:29.420 --> 05:34.180
She's terrible skinny and homely, Marilla. Come here, child, and let me have a look at you.

05:34.660 --> 05:40.660
Lawful heart, did anyone ever see such freckles? And hair as red as carrots. Come here, child, I say.

05:42.280 --> 05:48.600
Anne came there, but not exactly as Mrs. Rachel expected. With one bound she crossed the kitchen

05:48.600 --> 05:53.680
floor and stood before Mrs. Rachel, her face scarlet with anger, her lips quivering and

05:53.680 --> 05:56.580
her whole slender form trembling from head to foot.

05:57.480 --> 06:01.660
I hate you, she cried in a choked voice, stamping her foot on the floor.

06:02.380 --> 06:07.780
I hate you, I hate you, I hate you, a louder stamp with each assertion of hatred.

06:08.520 --> 06:12.360
How dare you call me skinny and ugly? How dare you say I'm freckled and redheaded?

06:12.760 --> 06:15.100
You are a rude, impolite, unfeeling woman.

06:16.540 --> 06:18.960
Anne exclaimed Marilla in consternation.

06:20.160 --> 06:25.820
But Anne continued to face Mrs. Rachel undauntedly, head up, eyes blazing, hands clenched,

06:25.820 --> 06:28.880
passionate indignation exhaling from her like an atmosphere.

06:30.000 --> 06:32.740
How dare you say such things about me, she repeated vehemently.

06:33.200 --> 06:35.160
How would you like to have such things said about you?

06:35.480 --> 06:39.920
How would you like to be told that you are fat and clumsy and probably hadn't a spark of imagination in you?

06:40.180 --> 06:43.860
I don't care if I do hurt your feelings by saying so. I hope I hurt them.

06:44.240 --> 06:48.680
You have hurt mine worse than they were ever hurt before, even by Mrs. Thomas's intoxicated husband.

06:48.980 --> 06:53.420
And I'll never forgive you for it. Never, never. Stamp, stamp.

06:55.160 --> 06:59.240
Did anybody ever see such a temper, exclaimed the horrified Mrs. Rachel.

07:00.800 --> 07:05.960
Anne, go to your room and stay there until I come up, said Marilla, recovering her powers of speech with difficulty.

07:07.840 --> 07:15.180
Anne, bursting into tears, rushed to the hall door, slammed it until the tins on the porch wall outside rattled in sympathy,

07:15.820 --> 07:18.420
and fled through the hall and up the stairs like a whirlwind.

07:19.120 --> 07:24.100
A subdued slam above told that the door of the East Gable had been shut with equal vehemence.

07:25.560 --> 07:31.500
Well, I don't envy you your job bringing that up, Marilla, said Mrs. Rachel, with unspeakable solemnity.

07:34.060 --> 07:37.880
Marilla opened her lips to say she knew not what of apology or deprecation.

07:38.540 --> 07:42.520
What she did say was a surprise to herself then and ever afterwards.

07:43.680 --> 07:46.180
You shouldn't have tweeted her about her looks, Rachel.

07:48.340 --> 07:55.500
Marilla Cuthbert, you don't mean to say that you are upholding her in such a terrible display of temper as we've just seen, demanded Mrs. Rachel indignantly.

07:56.980 --> 08:03.460
No, said Marilla slowly, I'm not trying to excuse her. She's been very naughty and I'll have to give her a talking to about it.

08:03.820 --> 08:09.400
But we must make allowances for her. She's never been taught what is right. And you were too hard on her, Rachel.

08:11.180 --> 08:15.900
Marilla could not help tacking on that last sentence, although she was again surprised at herself for doing it.

08:16.920 --> 08:19.580
Mrs. Rachel got up with an air of offended dignity.

08:20.840 --> 08:30.060
Well, I see that I'll have to be very careful what I say after this, Marilla, since the fine feelings of orphans, brought from goodness knows where, have to be considered before anything else.

08:30.500 --> 08:36.060
Oh no, I'm not vexed, don't worry yourself. I'm too sorry for you to leave any room for anger in my mind.

08:36.600 --> 08:38.300
You'll have your own troubles with that child.

08:39.000 --> 08:43.820
But if you'll take my advice, which I suppose you won't do, although I've brought up ten children and buried two,

08:43.820 --> 08:47.300
you'll do that talking to who you mentioned with a fair-sized birch switch.

08:47.920 --> 08:53.400
I should think that would be the most effective language for that kind of a child. Her temper matches her hair, I guess.

08:54.100 --> 08:57.880
Well, good evening, Marilla. I hope you'll come down to see me often, as usual.

08:58.400 --> 09:05.300
But you can't expect me to visit here again in a hurry, if I'm liable to be flown at and insulted in such a fashion. It's something new in my experience.

09:07.080 --> 09:12.520
Whereat Mrs. Rachel swept out and away, if a fat woman who always waddled could be said to sweep away.

09:12.520 --> 09:16.780
And Marilla, with a very solemn face, betook herself to the East Gable.

09:18.920 --> 09:22.480
On the way upstairs, she pondered uneasily as to what she ought to do.

09:23.260 --> 09:26.480
She felt no little dismay over the scene that had just been enacted.

09:27.340 --> 09:31.680
How unfortunate that Anne should have displayed such temper before Mrs. Rachel Lynde of all people.

09:32.920 --> 09:36.820
Then Marilla suddenly became aware of an uncomfortable and rebuking consciousness,

09:36.820 --> 09:43.600
that she felt more humiliation over this than sorrow over the discovery of such a serious defect in Anne's disposition.

09:44.740 --> 09:46.800
And how was she to punish her?

09:47.480 --> 09:54.400
The amiable suggestion of the birch switch, to the efficiency of which all of Mrs. Rachel's own children could have borne smarting testimony,

09:55.060 --> 09:59.240
did not appeal to Marilla. She did not believe she could whip a child.

10:00.360 --> 10:06.260
No, some other method of punishment must be found to bring Anne to a proper realization of the enormity of her offence.

10:08.520 --> 10:15.820
Marilla found Anne face downward on her bed, crying bitterly, quite oblivious of muddy boots on a clean counterpane.

10:18.000 --> 10:22.100
Anne, she said, not un-gently. No answer.

10:23.540 --> 10:28.300
Anne, with greater severity, get off that bed this minute and listen to what I have to say to you.

10:29.900 --> 10:33.680
Anne squirmed off the bed and sat rigidly on a chair beside it,

10:33.680 --> 10:38.240
her face swollen and tear-stained and her eyes fixed stubbornly on the floor.

10:39.680 --> 10:42.780
This is a nice way for you to behave, Anne. Aren't you ashamed of yourself?

10:43.640 --> 10:48.300
She hadn't any right to call me ugly and redheaded, retorted Anne, evasive and defiant.

10:49.440 --> 10:53.140
You hadn't any right to fly into such a fury and talk the way you did to her, Anne.

10:53.760 --> 10:56.280
I was ashamed of you, thoroughly ashamed of you.

10:56.660 --> 11:01.100
I wanted you to behave nicely to Mrs. Lind, and instead of that you have disgraced me.

11:01.520 --> 11:06.520
I'm sure I don't know why you should lose your temper like that, just because Mrs. Lind said you were red-haired and homely.

11:06.860 --> 11:08.300
You say it yourself often enough.

11:09.720 --> 11:14.180
Oh, but there's such a difference between saying a thing yourself and hearing other people say it, wailed Anne.

11:14.980 --> 11:19.280
You may know a thing as so, but you can't help hoping other people don't quite think it is.

11:19.760 --> 11:22.900
I suppose you think I have an awful temper, but I couldn't help it.

11:23.160 --> 11:28.300
When she said those things, something just rose right up in me and choked me. I had to fly out at her.

11:29.640 --> 11:32.600
Well, you made a fine exhibition of yourself, I must say.

11:33.200 --> 11:37.260
Mrs. Lind will have a nice story to tell about you everywhere, and she'll tell it too.

11:37.800 --> 11:40.640
It was a dreadful thing for you to lose your temper like that, Anne.

11:42.520 --> 11:48.240
Just imagine how you would feel if somebody told you to your face that you were skinny and ugly, pleaded Anne tearfully.

11:49.880 --> 11:52.640
An old remembrance suddenly rose up before Marilla.

11:53.560 --> 11:57.600
She had been a very small child when she had heard one aunt say of her to another.

11:58.300 --> 12:00.840
What a pity she is such a dark, homely little thing.

12:01.980 --> 12:05.160
Marilla was every day a fifty before the sting had gone out of that memory.

12:07.580 --> 12:13.660
I don't say that I think Mrs. Lind was exactly right in saying what she did to you, Anne, she admitted in a softer tone.

12:14.560 --> 12:18.880
Rachel is too outspoken, but that is no excuse for such behavior on your part.

12:19.480 --> 12:22.720
She was a stranger and an elderly person and my visitor.

12:23.140 --> 12:26.060
All three very good reasons why you should have been respectful to her.

12:26.060 --> 12:30.940
You are rude and saucy and Marilla had a saving inspiration of punishment.

12:31.660 --> 12:36.420
You must go to her and tell her you are very sorry for your bad temper and ask her to forgive you.

12:37.300 --> 12:41.240
I can never do that, said Anne, determinedly and darkly.

12:41.780 --> 12:43.800
You can punish me in any way you like, Marilla.

12:44.240 --> 12:51.040
You can shut me up in a dark, damp dungeon inhabited by snakes and toads and feed me only on bread and water and I shall not complain.

12:51.500 --> 12:54.120
But I cannot ask Mrs. Lind to forgive me.

12:55.760 --> 13:02.800
We're not in the habit of shutting people up in dark, damp dungeons, said Marilla, dryly, especially as they're rather scarce and avidly.

13:03.440 --> 13:10.160
But apologize to Mrs. Lind you must and shall and you'll stay here in your room until you can tell me you're willing to do it.

13:11.420 --> 13:18.260
I shall have to stay here forever then, said Anne, mournfully, because I can't tell Mrs. Lind I'm sorry I said those things to her.

13:18.260 --> 13:26.060
How can I? I'm not sorry. I'm sorry I vexed you, but I'm glad I told her just what I did. It was a great satisfaction.

13:26.840 --> 13:31.080
I can't say I'm sorry when I'm not, can I? I can't even imagine I'm sorry.

13:33.020 --> 13:38.040
Perhaps your imagination will be in better working order by the morning, said Marilla, rising to depart.

13:38.920 --> 13:43.200
You'll have the night to think over your conduct in and come to a better frame of mind.

13:43.200 --> 13:50.120
You said you would try to be a very good girl if we kept you at Green Gables, but I must say it hasn't seemed very much like it this evening.

13:51.880 --> 14:00.620
Leaving this Parthian shaft to rankle in Anne's stormy bosom, Marilla descended to the kitchen, grievously troubled in mind and vexed in soul.

14:01.500 --> 14:12.560
She was as angry with herself as with Anne, because, whenever she recalled Mrs. Rachel's dumbfounded countenance, her lips twitched with amusement and she felt a most reprehensible desire to laugh.

14:13.740 --> 14:21.780
End of chapter 9. Recorded January 22, 2006, in Longmont, Colorado.

